issue.title: Update the solar function docs to reflect that it accepts floats and not only ints
issue.body:
<!--

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- None

#### Possible Duplicates

- None

# Brief Summary
The docs for celery.schedules.solar state that long and lat are ints. This triggers a warning for some linters and also the example on the page uses the function with floats:

```
lat (int): The latitude of the observer.
lon (int): The longitude of the observer.
```

```
from celery.schedules import solar

app.conf.beat_schedule = {
    # Executes at sunset in Melbourne
    'add-at-melbourne-sunset': {
        'task': 'tasks.add',
        'schedule': solar('sunset', -37.81753, 144.96715),
        'args': (16, 16),
    },
}
```

# Design

describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.

Change the docstring to float

issue.title: SoftTimeLimitExceeded exception does not raise with embedded worker
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7871
Originally posted by **voqtuyen** November 2, 2022 I have a test case with the following files conftest.py ```python import pytest pytest_plugins = ("celery.contrib.pytest", ) @pytest.fixture(scope='session') def celery_config(): return { 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'rpc://' } ``` tasks.py ```python import time from celery import Celery from conftest import celery_config app = Celery() app.conf.update({ 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'cache+memcached://memcached:11211', 'soft_time_limit': 1 }) @app.task(bind=True, max_retries=2, soft_time_limit=1) def my_task(self, x, y): time.sleep(5) return x + y ``` tests_all.py ```python import pytest from tasks import app, my_task from celery.contrib.testing.worker import start_worker def test_my_task(): with start_worker(app, perform_ping_check=False, loglevel="INFO"): result = my_task.apply([2, 3], throw=True) result.get() ``` However, when I run pytest test_all.py does not raise SoftTimeLimitExceeded exception? Is there any wrong or what is the correct way to unittest it!

issue.title: At Least One Feature Request or Bug Fix Per Month Plan
issue.body:
Hi, all paid users,

 Firstly, thanks for your support! That means a lot to me. And for those who contributed to this project before by OpenCollective or code or other ways, please contact me and I will give you a free license.

This project is **five years old**, and I have maintained this project for five years. Over the past year, I didn't spend lots of time on this project because I've been busy with work, and there have been fewer updates. But I still keep doing bug fixes and small feature requests.  

Please believe that I have put unparalleled energy into this project. Feature requests and bug fixes are not done without any effort. For the sustainable development of this project, I will make some parts of this project (the C# part is completely rewritten) and the new ones added in the future as paid features.

**And, the open-source part of this project will still stay free, and free for always.**

Now I'm trying to start an "At Least One Feature Request or Bug Fix Per Month Plan", which means that I will at least make one feature request or bug fix done every month for paid users, and this plugin will update monthly. This basically improves the value of this plugin for paid users and makes this plugin live longer and better.

Please just fire your feature request or bug report, and I will try to fix them. And don't forget to upload your screenshots of "Help -> Register or Manage Licenses". And if someone else already fired a feature request or bug report, please 👍 for that.

Happy coding~

issue.title: Support device renaming
issue.body:
# 🚀 Feature Request

### 📝 Description

It would probably a good idea to implement the possibility to rename a device. Everyone makes typo mistakes so it would be a good fast way to rename the device instead of delete it and make a new one.

### ✨ Describe the solution you'd like

It could something like a edit button in the device manager on the "active devices" site just like the delete button on the inactive site

# Description
<!--

The [serialization docs](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/calling.html#serializers) include a section on msgpack:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25310870/198069515-4379228e-b743-453f-b1e3-0c4ae4b60da3.png)

Specifically I'm referring to 

> It’s very young however, and support should be considered experimental at this point.

It seems this sentence was added 12 years back in [this commit](https://github.com/celery/celery/commit/c9a0fe455593da228d80ebedb3273656408b66f9), which seems to have been around version 2.2.0.




# Suggestions
<!-- Please provide us suggestions for how to fix the documentation -->

I think it'd be good to revise the docs. I don't think this is accurate any longer. Do you agree? :slightly_smiling_face:

issue.title: Canvas starting with a group does not respect a countdown applied to whole canvas
issue.body:
# Checklist - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [ ] This has already been asked to the [discussions forum](https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions) first. - [x] I have read the relevant section in the [contribution guide](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/master/contributing.html#other-bugs) on reporting bugs. - [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Bug+Report%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for similar or identical bug reports. (#4405 may be related, but I'm not sure) - [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Bugfix%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for existing proposed fixes. - [ ] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master) to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch. - [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway). #4405 may be related, as mentioned above ## Mandatory Debugging Information - [x] I have included the output of ``celery -A proj report`` in the issue. (if you are not able to do this, then at least specify the Celery version affected). - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [x] I have included the contents of ``pip freeze`` in the issue. - [ ] I have included all the versions of all the external dependencies required to reproduce this bug. ## Optional Debugging Information - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one Python version and/or implementation. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one version of the message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one operating system. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one workers pool. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue with autoscaling, retries, ETA/Countdown & rate limits disabled. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue after downgrading and/or upgrading Celery and its dependencies. ## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates #### Related Issues - #4405 #### Possible Duplicates - None ## Environment & Settings **Celery version**: 5.3.0b1 (dawn-chorus)
celery report Output:

software -> celery:5.3.0b1 (dawn-chorus) kombu:5.3.0b2 py:3.8.12 billiard:4.0.2 redis:4.1.4 platform -> system:Linux arch:64bit, ELF kernel version:5.4.0-131-generic imp:CPython loader -> celery.loaders.app.AppLoader settings -> transport:redis results:redis:/// accept_content: ['json', 'pickle'] event_serializer: 'json' result_serializer: 'pickle' task_serializer: 'pickle' broker_url: 'redis://localhost:6379//' deprecated_settings: None result_backend: 'redis:///'

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Celery Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Kombu Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

adc-streaming==2.0.0 amqp==5.1.1 astroid==2.4.2 backports.entry-points-selectable==1.1.0 billiard==4.0.2 cachy==0.3.0 celery @ git+https://github.com/celery/celery.git@e0b0af6c7af9f7a127ae0321dc4e798433c89592 certifi==2021.10.8 cffi==1.15.1 charset-normalizer==2.1.1 click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 confluent-kafka==1.8.2 crashtest==0.3.1 cryptography==36.0.2 Deprecated==1.2.13 distlib==0.3.2 filelock==3.0.12 future==0.18.2 hop-client==0.5.0 idna==3.4 igwn-auth-utils==0.3.1 isort==5.6.3 kombu==5.3.0b2 lazy-object-proxy==1.4.3 ligo-gracedb==2.8.0 lockfile==0.12.2 mccabe==0.6.1 msgpack==1.0.2 packaging==21.3 pastel==0.2.1 pkginfo==1.7.1 platformdirs==2.3.0 pluggy==1.0.0 prompt-toolkit==3.0.28 pycparser==2.21 PyJWT==2.6.0 pylev==1.4.0 pylint==2.6.0 pyparsing==3.0.7 pytz==2021.3 redis==4.1.4 requests==2.28.1 safe-netrc==1.0.0 scitokens==1.7.2 shellingham==1.4.0 six==1.16.0 toml==0.10.2 tqdm==4.62.3 typing_extensions==4.4.0 urllib3==1.26.12 vine==5.0.0 virtualenv==20.7.2 wcwidth==0.2.5 wrapt==1.13.3 xmltodict==0.12.0

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

Project tree ```bash $ tree proj/ proj/ ├── __init__.py └── tasks.py ``` File contents ```bash $ cat proj/__init__.py from celery import Celery app = Celery('tasks', broker = 'redis://') app.conf['result_backend'] = app.conf.broker_url app.add_defaults( dict( accept_content = ['json', 'pickle'], event_serializer = 'json', result_serializer = 'pickle', task_serializer = 'pickle' ) ) app.autodiscover_tasks([__name__]) $ cat proj/tasks.py from . import app @app.task def add(x, y): return x + y @app.task def prod(x, y): return x * y ``` Start worker with ```bash $ celery -A proj worker -l info -c 2 ``` Then run following script ```python from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ```

# Expected Behavior Since a countdown has been placed, no task should execute until the countdown has expired. # Actual Behavior If a canvas starts with a `group`, and has chained tasks, the group is executed right away. For example in my minimal script above, there is the following canvas ``` canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) ``` The `group` containing the two `add` tasks are evaluated rightaway in the queue. The timeout kicks in only after this. This is seen in the log of the worker (see timestamp of result 3, 7 vs. 11, 15, 19): ``` [2022-10-24 23:10:04,176: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: searching for neighbors [2022-10-24 23:10:04,177: WARNING/MainProcess] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:10:05,183: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: all alone [2022-10-24 23:10:05,201: INFO/MainProcess] celery@deep-ThinkPad-P53 ready. [2022-10-24 23:13:33,585: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,586: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,589: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] succeeded in 0.002615050001622876s: 3 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,591: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-2] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-2] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] succeeded in 0.00721587799853296s: 7 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,597: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-1] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] succeeded in 0.008149747001880314s: 11 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,602: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] succeeded in 0.0008764769991103094s: 15 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] succeeded in 0.00035578700044425204s: 19 ``` The tasks starting `ce4dfe2e` and `e89c93a0` are received and are evaluated immediately giving results 3 and 7. The tasks that are chained to the group evaluate after the timeout is expired (note the timing for the task starting `864c3c54`). ### A few other observations - If there are chained tasks after the group, then setting `countdown` to the group directly is not respected. For example, changing minimal example to ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) # set countdown here canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` Gives all results rightaway: ``` Result = 19 Time elapsed(s) 0.03932476043701172 ``` However, if there are no chained tasks i.e., just the `group`, then the behavior is as expect. For example, ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` will print ``` Result = [3, 7] Time elapsed(s) 10.034985542297363 ```

issue.title: Timers registered in worker start are getting cancelled on consumer close
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7843
Originally posted by **meensu23** October 21, 2022 I register some tasks during worker start ``` class WorkerBoot(bootsteps.StartStopStep): requires = {"celery.worker.components:Pool", "celery.worker.components:Timer"} ... def __init__(self, worker, **kwargs) -> None: def start(self, worker): ... worker.timer.call_repeatedly( self.state_refresh_interval, self.some_function, (worker,), priority=10, ) ... ``` What I observe is after a connection loss (with amq) and restart the above timer does not fire. I printed the timer ref above and I see the same timer ref being used in worker and consumer. And as per https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/34533ab44d2a6492004bc3df44dc04ad5c6611e7/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py#L443 I see the timer is being cleared. ``` consumerboot consumer.timer= workerboot worker.timer= ``` Does worker and consumer use the same timer - documentation seem to suggest they use different (https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/extending.html?highlight=consumer%20boot#id8). What timer should I be using in the worker?

issue.title: Celery fills Redis Broker with results without setting TTL - resulting in OOM of Redis
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7776
Originally posted by **Flauschbaellchen** September 27, 2022 I have an issue in our application: When running Celery tasks, Celery keeps track of the tasks saving metadata (and the task's result) into the Broker's database. This data is however never deleted, which results in OOM of Redis eventually. ### Details I'm using the Redis backend. After running 1-3 tasks, the Redis database consists of the following entries: ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> keys * 1) "_kombu.binding.w3syse.queues.default" 2) "_kombu.binding.celery.pidbox" 3) "7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786" 4) "_kombu.binding.celeryev" ``` (I've set `task_default_queue = "w3syse.queues.default"`) Celery created the additional key `7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786` which tracks a task. The content is like the following: ``` {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "SUCCESS", "result": null, "traceback": null, "children": []} {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "STARTED", "result": {"pid": 1, "hostname": "celery@worker-server-7889c959d7-5mcmp"}, "traceback": null, "children": []} ``` The issue is, that those keys are never deleted, spamming the whole Redis database to such an extend, that the size is greater than the RAM of the machine and Redis is not able to run anymore (64GB+). This happens regularly if running several hundreds of tasks per second. After some research, I've found that the RedisBackend should be responsible of deleting such keys automatically on its own: https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/4f54119b822374533934943fa41ba68011295489/celery/backends/redis.py#L203 The TTL is 1 day (default) and can be adjusted by setting `result_expires` (see: https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/configuration.html#result-expires). I tried to set it to `5` (5 seconds), however, when checking the TTL of the key, Redis always returns `-1`, which means "No expire": ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> ttl 7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786 (integer) -1 ``` ### Environment Versions of packages: * celery[redis]==5.2.7 * django-celery-beat==2.3.0 * kombu==5.2.4 * redis==3.5.3 Redis server is 7.0.4. Other settings: ``` CELERY_RESULT_BACKEND = "rpc://" CELERY_ACCEPT_CONTENT = ["application/json"] CELERY_TASK_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_RESULT_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_TIMEZONE = TIME_ZONE CELERY_ENABLE_UTC = True CELERY_BEAT_SCHEDULER = "django_celery_beat.schedulers:DatabaseScheduler" CELERY_TASK_SEND_SENT_EVENT = True CELERY_WORKER_SEND_TASK_EVENTS = True CELERY_TASK_TRACK_STARTED = True ``` Can someone reproduce this issue/bug or can give me a hint if I need to adjust a setting? - Thanks a lot!

```

Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.

All packages:

```
❯❯ pip list
Package            Version
------------------ -------
amqp               5.1.1
cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 5.0.0

pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0

```

The possible reason may be the `importlib-metadata`:

```
❯❯ pip install importlib-metadata==4.13.0
....
Successfully installed importlib-metadata-4.13.0
❯❯ python
Python 3.7.12 (default, Jan 26 2022, 16:07:16)
[Clang 13.0.0 (clang-1300.0.29.3)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.

Everything all right and now the packages are:

```

Package            Version
------------------ -------

cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 4.13.0
kombu              5.2.4
pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0
typing_extensions  4.4.0

The only difference is the version of `importlib-metadata`.

issue.title: SQS Batch SendMessage
issue.body:
Hi all,

We're recently transitioned from using SQS natively to using Celery. We have some use cases where we send a bunch of tasks - for example, canceling every payment belonging to an entity. When we started using celery we noticed that each message is enqueued individually, and there's nothing in the documentation that I could find. Searching through Kombu, I see that batch get is supported, but batch put does not seem to be supported. In my ideal world, we can support batch messaging in Celery to improve our app's throughput. Let me know if that makes sense!

Docs: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/APIReference/API_SendMessageBatch.html

celery report Output:

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Celery Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Kombu Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

``` amqp==5.1.1 async-timeout==4.0.2 billiard==4.0.2 celery @ https://github.com/celery/celery/zipball/master click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 Deprecated==1.2.13 kombu==5.3.0b1 packaging==21.3 prompt-toolkit==3.0.31 pyparsing==3.0.9 pytz==2022.4 redis==4.2.2 six==1.16.0 typing-extensions==4.3.0 vine==5.0.0 wcwidth==0.2.5 wrapt==1.14.1 ```

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

`worker.py` ```python import logging import logging.handlers from celery import Celery import celery_tasks APP_NAME = 'log_test' LOG_FORMAT = '[%(levelname)-.1s %(asctime)s %(name)s] %(message)s' WORKER_LOG_FILE = 'worker-run.log' CELERY_SETTINGS = {'broker_url': 'redis://localhost/', 'result_backend': 'redis://localhost/','worker_hijack_root_logger': False} def create_celery_app(): celery_app = Celery(APP_NAME, config_source=CELERY_SETTINGS, set_as_current=True) celery_app.finalize() celery_app.set_default() return celery_app app = create_celery_app() def setup_rotating_logger(): logfile = WORKER_LOG_FILE handler = logging.handlers.TimedRotatingFileHandler(WORKER_LOG_FILE, interval=30, when='S') handler.setFormatter(logging.Formatter(LOG_FORMAT)) logging.root.addHandler(handler) logging.root.setLevel(logging.INFO) if __name__ == '__main__': setup_rotating_logger() kwargs = {'without_gossip': True, 'concurrency': 1, 'prefetch_multiplier': 1,'loglevel': logging.INFO} worker = app.Worker(**kwargs) worker.start() ``` `tasks.py` ```python import logging import time import celery from celery import shared_task from celery.app.task import Task @shared_task(base=Task) def echo_task(taskdata): logger = logging.getLogger() logger.error(f'Worker run: {taskdata["a"]}') time.sleep(1) taskdata['a'] += 1 return taskdata @shared_task(base=Task) def run_task(): exec_list = [echo_task.s()] * 100 async_res = celery.chain(*exec_list)({'a': 1}) async_res.ignored = True ``` `run.py` ```python from worker import app from tasks import run_task if __name__ == '__main__': run_task.s().apply_async(ignore_result=True) ``` Steps: 1. Run worker with: `>>> python worker.py` 2. Call the tasks with: `>>> python run.py`

# Expected Behavior As the tasks are executing and logging, when the `TimedRotatingHandler` does rollover and creates an old and a new log file, all the logs post that should be logged to the latest file (`worker-run.log`). But some logs can also be seen getting logged to the file which was last rolled over by the rotating handler. # Actual Behavior All the logs should be recorded to the latest log file (`worker-run.log`) only. PS: I've tried using this library: https://pypi.org/project/multiprocessing-logging/ by calling `multiprocessing_logging.install_mp_handler()` right after calling `setup_rotating_logger()` and it seemed to fix the logging.

issue.title: Understanding pidbox queue names
issue.body:
I'm trying to debug a piece of third-party software that uses Celery (and therefore, indirectly, Kombu) for a remote control mailbox. I apologize for asking RTFM-able questions, but I spent a bit of time and could not unravel these.

It looks like somewhere in the stack a queue is created with a name like `celery@hostname.reply.celery.pidbox`. Note that this includes my computer's hostname, but some references I've found seem to use UUIDs instead of the hostname.

1. What is the `celery@` part called / referring to? Actually what are all the parts of this referring to? It is kind of un-Googleable.
2. Is there a reason to override the `celery@` (e.g., to associate it with the application user associated with the queue)? If so, how?
3. How do I override the use of the hostname?
4. In what cases is a UUID used instead of the hostname?
5. What is responsible for generating these names, Kombu or Celery? Does it vary based on the selected backend (e.g., RabbitMQ vs Redis)?

issue.title: Kombu using deprecated importlib-metadata shims
issue.body:
Hi devs,

I'm facing the following issue when importing kombu in my code. I've narrowed it down to the library `importlib-metadata`'s most recent release. Here's how to reproduce it:

1. Create a new virtual environment

```bash
python -m venv .venv
```

2. Activate virtual environment

```bash
source .venv/bin/activate
```

3. Install kombu

```bash
pip install kombu
```

4. Confirm that `importlib-metadata` release 5.0.0 is installed

```bash
pip freeze | grep importlib-metadata
```

5. Run python and import kombu via `kombu.entity`

```
>>> from kombu.entity import Queue
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/entity.py", line 7, in <module>
    from .serialization import prepare_accept_content
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/serialization.py", line 440, in <module>
    for ep, args in entrypoints('kombu.serializers'):  # pragma: no cover
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/utils/compat.py", line 82, in entrypoints
    for ep in importlib_metadata.entry_points().get(namespace, [])
AttributeError: 'EntryPoints' object has no attribute 'get'
```

It is stated in the most recent release of the library (https://github.com/python/importlib_metadata/blob/v5.0.0/CHANGES.rst)
> #97, #284, #300: Removed compatibility shims for deprecated entry point interfaces.

I can confirm kombu still works with the most recent release in v4 (e.g. 4.13.0).

Since this `importlib-metadata` release 5.0.0 is installed alongside a fresh kombu installation, this could be problematic for new users down the line. I'm suggesting to limit the version to <5.0.0 to ensure usability.

issue.title: How to avoid BrokenPipeError if a message has been acked (acks_late)
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7762
Originally posted by **stanleyli60** September 15, 2022 Hi all, I am using Celery 5.2.2 + RabbitMQ setup. My task has been configured as acks_late where we only acknowledge the task when finished. i.e. @shared_task(bind=True, acks_late=True) def execute_sth() I have multiple celery workers setup with (concurrency = 8 and worker_prefetch_multiplier= 1). The task is expected to last from 10 min to 20min. What has happened is that the task is delivered to one of the worker and it started working on it. And then in the middle of its execution, the task is re-delivered to another worker and I have code to complete the task right away if it is executed for the second time. So the second worker acks the message earlier. When the first worker is finished and tries to ack on the same message, I am getting a broken pipe error. Below is some example logs: 2022-09-15 12:14:35 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-dad78da2d996eb9b2e00 received 5391871 . . . (first worker received the task and start working on it) . . 2022-09-15 12:20:28 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-c0e6a4e6e9d1d9d05000 received 5391871 (second worker received the same task and start working on it. And finished right away and ack the message) . . 2022-09-15 12:22:15 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-dad78da2d996eb9b2e00 succeeded (first worker finally finished and tries to ack on the message) Getting the following exception message: Message Couldn't ack 206, reason:"BrokenPipeError(32, 'Broken pipe')" Any idea on how I should avoid this problem?

issue.title: Support task pool shutdowns on idle
issue.body:
<!--
Please fill this template entirely and do not erase parts of it.
We reserve the right to close without a response
feature requests which are incomplete.
-->
# Checklist
<!--
To check an item on the list replace [ ] with [x].
-->

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- Could not find anything for the key terms I searched

#### Possible Duplicates

- This seems similar to where a celery worker could be "bursted" and shutdown once the queue is empty here #6687. Would be a similar feature

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the feature does
and why it is needed.
-->

Add the ability to shutdown a worker/pool, not entirely knowledgeable of underlying processes, when a queue is empty. I currently have the issue with tensorflow not deallocating GPU and the only solution would be to use multiprocessing, which I presume celery uses under the hood for certain pools, and it seems janky to have a task start another process, which just complicates things. Thus a method of "restarting" the pool after no tasks have been submitted for X amount of time would be nice.

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
None

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this feature is going to behave.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->

It would be nice to start a celery worker have it process whatever is in the queue and once it's done close/restart the pool process so that any allocated memory would be cleared. This is sort of similar to max-tasks-per-child, but that I noticed only restarts when a NEW task is assigned not when it's idle.

Some logic that would make this work better is that the pool wouldn't restart unless if it has already processed some tasks. In my case the queue could be empty majority of the time, but I occasionally have some peak GPU load for site tensorflow stuff and would like the memory to be cleared once the queue sits empty for let's say 5 minutes. I've looked at tf issues and it seems like there really isn't any non-obscure way to clear the memory without ending the process/clearing cuda/resetting the device which is not what I want. 

## Proposed UI/UX
<!--
Please provide your ideas for the API, CLI options,
configuration key names etc. that will be introduced for this feature.
-->

Add a flag of the sort, possibly way better names, `--child-empty-timeout Xs` which would reset the worker after X seconds of idle AFTER processing something.

## Diagrams
<!--
Please include any diagrams that might be relevant
to the implementation of this feature such as:
* Class Diagrams
* Sequence Diagrams
* Activity Diagrams
You can drag and drop images into the text box to attach them to this issue.
-->
N/A

## Alternatives
<!--
If you have considered any alternative implementations
describe them in detail below.
-->

Simply have the `max-tasks-per-child` terminate and recreate the pool immediately after the N tasks is complete.

issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7871
Originally posted by **voqtuyen** November 2, 2022 I have a test case with the following files conftest.py ```python import pytest pytest_plugins = ("celery.contrib.pytest", ) @pytest.fixture(scope='session') def celery_config(): return { 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'rpc://' } ``` tasks.py ```python import time from celery import Celery from conftest import celery_config app = Celery() app.conf.update({ 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'cache+memcached://memcached:11211', 'soft_time_limit': 1 }) @app.task(bind=True, max_retries=2, soft_time_limit=1) def my_task(self, x, y): time.sleep(5) return x + y ``` tests_all.py ```python import pytest from tasks import app, my_task from celery.contrib.testing.worker import start_worker def test_my_task(): with start_worker(app, perform_ping_check=False, loglevel="INFO"): result = my_task.apply([2, 3], throw=True) result.get() ``` However, when I run pytest test_all.py does not raise SoftTimeLimitExceeded exception? Is there any wrong or what is the correct way to unittest it!

Hi, all paid users,

 Firstly, thanks for your support! That means a lot to me. And for those who contributed to this project before by OpenCollective or code or other ways, please contact me and I will give you a free license.

This project is **five years old**, and I have maintained this project for five years. Over the past year, I didn't spend lots of time on this project because I've been busy with work, and there have been fewer updates. But I still keep doing bug fixes and small feature requests.  

Please believe that I have put unparalleled energy into this project. Feature requests and bug fixes are not done without any effort. For the sustainable development of this project, I will make some parts of this project (the C# part is completely rewritten) and the new ones added in the future as paid features.

**And, the open-source part of this project will still stay free, and free for always.**

Now I'm trying to start an "At Least One Feature Request or Bug Fix Per Month Plan", which means that I will at least make one feature request or bug fix done every month for paid users, and this plugin will update monthly. This basically improves the value of this plugin for paid users and makes this plugin live longer and better.

Please just fire your feature request or bug report, and I will try to fix them. And don't forget to upload your screenshots of "Help -> Register or Manage Licenses". And if someone else already fired a feature request or bug report, please 👍 for that.

Happy coding~

(if you are not able to do this, then at least specify the Celery version affected). - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [x] I have included the contents of ``pip freeze`` in the issue. - [ ] I have included all the versions of all the external dependencies required to reproduce this bug. ## Optional Debugging Information - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one Python version and/or implementation. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one version of the message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one operating system. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one workers pool. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue with autoscaling, retries, ETA/Countdown & rate limits disabled. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue after downgrading and/or upgrading Celery and its dependencies. ## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates #### Related Issues - #4405 #### Possible Duplicates - None ## Environment & Settings **Celery version**: 5.3.0b1 (dawn-chorus)

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

Project tree ```bash $ tree proj/ proj/ ├── __init__.py └── tasks.py ``` File contents ```bash $ cat proj/__init__.py from celery import Celery app = Celery('tasks', broker = 'redis://') app.conf['result_backend'] = app.conf.broker_url app.add_defaults( dict( accept_content = ['json', 'pickle'], event_serializer = 'json', result_serializer = 'pickle', task_serializer = 'pickle' ) ) app.autodiscover_tasks([__name__]) $ cat proj/tasks.py from . import app @app.task def add(x, y): return x + y @app.task def prod(x, y): return x * y ``` Start worker with ```bash $ celery -A proj worker -l info -c 2 ``` Then run following script ```python from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ```

# Expected Behavior Since a countdown has been placed, no task should execute until the countdown has expired. # Actual Behavior If a canvas starts with a `group`, and has chained tasks, the group is executed right away. For example in my minimal script above, there is the following canvas ``` canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) ``` The `group` containing the two `add` tasks are evaluated rightaway in the queue. The timeout kicks in only after this. This is seen in the log of the worker (see timestamp of result 3, 7 vs. 11, 15, 19): ``` [2022-10-24 23:10:04,176: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: searching for neighbors [2022-10-24 23:10:04,177: WARNING/MainProcess] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:10:05,183: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: all alone [2022-10-24 23:10:05,201: INFO/MainProcess] celery@deep-ThinkPad-P53 ready. [2022-10-24 23:13:33,585: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,586: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,589: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] succeeded in 0.002615050001622876s: 3 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,591: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-2] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-2] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] succeeded in 0.00721587799853296s: 7 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,597: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-1] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] succeeded in 0.008149747001880314s: 11 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,602: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] succeeded in 0.0008764769991103094s: 15 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] succeeded in 0.00035578700044425204s: 19 ``` The tasks starting `ce4dfe2e` and `e89c93a0` are received and are evaluated immediately giving results 3 and 7. The tasks that are chained to the group evaluate after the timeout is expired (note the timing for the task starting `864c3c54`). ### A few other observations - If there are chained tasks after the group, then setting `countdown` to the group directly is not respected. For example, changing minimal example to ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) # set countdown here canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` Gives all results rightaway: ``` Result = 19 Time elapsed(s) 0.03932476043701172 ``` However, if there are no chained tasks i.e., just the `group`, then the behavior is as expect. For example, ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` will print ``` Result = [3, 7] Time elapsed(s) 10.034985542297363 ```

issue.title: Timers registered in worker start are getting cancelled on consumer close
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7843
Originally posted by **meensu23** October 21, 2022 I register some tasks during worker start ``` class WorkerBoot(bootsteps.StartStopStep): requires = {"celery.worker.components:Pool", "celery.worker.components:Timer"} ... def __init__(self, worker, **kwargs) -> None: def start(self, worker): ... worker.timer.call_repeatedly( self.state_refresh_interval, self.some_function, (worker,), priority=10, ) ... ``` What I observe is after a connection loss (with amq) and restart the above timer does not fire. I printed the timer ref above and I see the same timer ref being used in worker and consumer. And as per https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/34533ab44d2a6492004bc3df44dc04ad5c6611e7/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py#L443 I see the timer is being cleared. ``` consumerboot consumer.timer= workerboot worker.timer= ``` Does worker and consumer use the same timer - documentation seem to suggest they use different (https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/extending.html?highlight=consumer%20boot#id8). What timer should I be using in the worker?

issue.title: Celery fills Redis Broker with results without setting TTL - resulting in OOM of Redis
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7776
Originally posted by **Flauschbaellchen** September 27, 2022 I have an issue in our application: When running Celery tasks, Celery keeps track of the tasks saving metadata (and the task's result) into the Broker's database. This data is however never deleted, which results in OOM of Redis eventually. ### Details I'm using the Redis backend. After running 1-3 tasks, the Redis database consists of the following entries: ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> keys * 1) "_kombu.binding.w3syse.queues.default" 2) "_kombu.binding.celery.pidbox" 3) "7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786" 4) "_kombu.binding.celeryev" ``` (I've set `task_default_queue = "w3syse.queues.default"`) Celery created the additional key `7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786` which tracks a task. The content is like the following: ``` {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "SUCCESS", "result": null, "traceback": null, "children": []} {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "STARTED", "result": {"pid": 1, "hostname": "celery@worker-server-7889c959d7-5mcmp"}, "traceback": null, "children": []} ``` The issue is, that those keys are never deleted, spamming the whole Redis database to such an extend, that the size is greater than the RAM of the machine and Redis is not able to run anymore (64GB+). This happens regularly if running several hundreds of tasks per second. After some research, I've found that the RedisBackend should be responsible of deleting such keys automatically on its own: https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/4f54119b822374533934943fa41ba68011295489/celery/backends/redis.py#L203 The TTL is 1 day (default) and can be adjusted by setting `result_expires` (see: https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/configuration.html#result-expires). I tried to set it to `5` (5 seconds), however, when checking the TTL of the key, Redis always returns `-1`, which means "No expire": ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> ttl 7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786 (integer) -1 ``` ### Environment Versions of packages: * celery[redis]==5.2.7 * django-celery-beat==2.3.0 * kombu==5.2.4 * redis==3.5.3 Redis server is 7.0.4. Other settings: ``` CELERY_RESULT_BACKEND = "rpc://" CELERY_ACCEPT_CONTENT = ["application/json"] CELERY_TASK_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_RESULT_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_TIMEZONE = TIME_ZONE CELERY_ENABLE_UTC = True CELERY_BEAT_SCHEDULER = "django_celery_beat.schedulers:DatabaseScheduler" CELERY_TASK_SEND_SENT_EVENT = True CELERY_WORKER_SEND_TASK_EVENTS = True CELERY_TASK_TRACK_STARTED = True ``` Can someone reproduce this issue/bug or can give me a hint if I need to adjust a setting? - Thanks a lot!

Hi, I found some errors about import like this:

```

ImportError: cannot import name 'Exchange' from 'kombu' (***/.pyenv/versions/temp/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/__init__.py)

All packages:

```
❯❯ pip list
Package            Version
------------------ -------
amqp               5.1.1
cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 5.0.0

pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0
typing_extensions  4.4.0

zipp               3.9.0
```

The possible reason may be the `importlib-metadata`:

```
❯❯ pip install importlib-metadata==4.13.0
....
Successfully installed importlib-metadata-4.13.0
❯❯ python
Python 3.7.12 (default, Jan 26 2022, 16:07:16)
[Clang 13.0.0 (clang-1300.0.29.3)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> from kombu import Exchange
>>> 
```

Everything all right and now the packages are:

```

Package            Version
------------------ -------
amqp               5.1.1
cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 4.13.0
kombu              5.2.4
pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0
typing_extensions  4.4.0

issue.title: SQS Batch SendMessage
issue.body:
Hi all,

We're recently transitioned from using SQS natively to using Celery. We have some use cases where we send a bunch of tasks - for example, canceling every payment belonging to an entity. When we started using celery we noticed that each message is enqueued individually, and there's nothing in the documentation that I could find. Searching through Kombu, I see that batch get is supported, but batch put does not seem to be supported. In my ideal world, we can support batch messaging in Celery to improve our app's throughput. Let me know if that makes sense!

Docs: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/APIReference/API_SendMessageBatch.html

celery report Output:

``` ```

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Celery Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Kombu Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

``` amqp==5.1.1 async-timeout==4.0.2 billiard==4.0.2 celery @ https://github.com/celery/celery/zipball/master click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 Deprecated==1.2.13 kombu==5.3.0b1 packaging==21.3 prompt-toolkit==3.0.31 pyparsing==3.0.9 pytz==2022.4 redis==4.2.2 six==1.16.0 typing-extensions==4.3.0 vine==5.0.0 wcwidth==0.2.5 wrapt==1.14.1 ```

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

`worker.py` ```python import logging import logging.handlers from celery import Celery import celery_tasks APP_NAME = 'log_test' LOG_FORMAT = '[%(levelname)-.1s %(asctime)s %(name)s] %(message)s' WORKER_LOG_FILE = 'worker-run.log' CELERY_SETTINGS = {'broker_url': 'redis://localhost/', 'result_backend': 'redis://localhost/','worker_hijack_root_logger': False} def create_celery_app(): celery_app = Celery(APP_NAME, config_source=CELERY_SETTINGS, set_as_current=True) celery_app.finalize() celery_app.set_default() return celery_app app = create_celery_app() def setup_rotating_logger(): logfile = WORKER_LOG_FILE handler = logging.handlers.TimedRotatingFileHandler(WORKER_LOG_FILE, interval=30, when='S') handler.setFormatter(logging.Formatter(LOG_FORMAT)) logging.root.addHandler(handler) logging.root.setLevel(logging.INFO) if __name__ == '__main__': setup_rotating_logger() kwargs = {'without_gossip': True, 'concurrency': 1, 'prefetch_multiplier': 1,'loglevel': logging.INFO} worker = app.Worker(**kwargs) worker.start() ``` `tasks.py` ```python import logging import time import celery from celery import shared_task from celery.app.task import Task @shared_task(base=Task) def echo_task(taskdata): logger = logging.getLogger() logger.error(f'Worker run: {taskdata["a"]}') time.sleep(1) taskdata['a'] += 1 return taskdata @shared_task(base=Task) def run_task(): exec_list = [echo_task.s()] * 100 async_res = celery.chain(*exec_list)({'a': 1}) async_res.ignored = True ``` `run.py` ```python from worker import app from tasks import run_task if __name__ == '__main__': run_task.s().apply_async(ignore_result=True) ``` Steps: 1. Run worker with: `>>> python worker.py` 2. Call the tasks with: `>>> python run.py`

# Expected Behavior As the tasks are executing and logging, when the `TimedRotatingHandler` does rollover and creates an old and a new log file, all the logs post that should be logged to the latest file (`worker-run.log`). But some logs can also be seen getting logged to the file which was last rolled over by the rotating handler. # Actual Behavior All the logs should be recorded to the latest log file (`worker-run.log`) only. PS: I've tried using this library: https://pypi.org/project/multiprocessing-logging/ by calling `multiprocessing_logging.install_mp_handler()` right after calling `setup_rotating_logger()` and it seemed to fix the logging.

issue.title: Understanding pidbox queue names
issue.body:
I'm trying to debug a piece of third-party software that uses Celery (and therefore, indirectly, Kombu) for a remote control mailbox. I apologize for asking RTFM-able questions, but I spent a bit of time and could not unravel these.

It looks like somewhere in the stack a queue is created with a name like `celery@hostname.reply.celery.pidbox`. Note that this includes my computer's hostname, but some references I've found seem to use UUIDs instead of the hostname.

1. What is the `celery@` part called / referring to? Actually what are all the parts of this referring to? It is kind of un-Googleable.
2. Is there a reason to override the `celery@` (e.g., to associate it with the application user associated with the queue)? If so, how?
3. How do I override the use of the hostname?
4. In what cases is a UUID used instead of the hostname?
5. What is responsible for generating these names, Kombu or Celery? Does it vary based on the selected backend (e.g., RabbitMQ vs Redis)?

I'm facing the following issue when importing kombu in my code. I've narrowed it down to the library `importlib-metadata`'s most recent release. Here's how to reproduce it:

1. Create a new virtual environment

```bash
python -m venv .venv
```

2. Activate virtual environment

```bash
source .venv/bin/activate
```

3. Install kombu

```bash
pip install kombu
```

4. Confirm that `importlib-metadata` release 5.0.0 is installed

```bash
pip freeze | grep importlib-metadata
```

5. Run python and import kombu via `kombu.entity`

```
>>> from kombu.entity import Queue
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/entity.py", line 7, in <module>
    from .serialization import prepare_accept_content
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/serialization.py", line 440, in <module>
    for ep, args in entrypoints('kombu.serializers'):  # pragma: no cover
  File "/Users/muhammad.azman/Projects/drilling-management-ds/.venv2/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/utils/compat.py", line 82, in entrypoints
    for ep in importlib_metadata.entry_points().get(namespace, [])
AttributeError: 'EntryPoints' object has no attribute 'get'
```

It is stated in the most recent release of the library (https://github.com/python/importlib_metadata/blob/v5.0.0/CHANGES.rst)
> #97, #284, #300: Removed compatibility shims for deprecated entry point interfaces.

I can confirm kombu still works with the most recent release in v4 (e.g. 4.13.0).

Since this `importlib-metadata` release 5.0.0 is installed alongside a fresh kombu installation, this could be problematic for new users down the line. I'm suggesting to limit the version to <5.0.0 to ensure usability.

issue.title: How to avoid BrokenPipeError if a message has been acked (acks_late)
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7762
Originally posted by **stanleyli60** September 15, 2022 Hi all, I am using Celery 5.2.2 + RabbitMQ setup. My task has been configured as acks_late where we only acknowledge the task when finished. i.e. @shared_task(bind=True, acks_late=True) def execute_sth() I have multiple celery workers setup with (concurrency = 8 and worker_prefetch_multiplier= 1). The task is expected to last from 10 min to 20min. What has happened is that the task is delivered to one of the worker and it started working on it. And then in the middle of its execution, the task is re-delivered to another worker and I have code to complete the task right away if it is executed for the second time. So the second worker acks the message earlier. When the first worker is finished and tries to ack on the same message, I am getting a broken pipe error. Below is some example logs: 2022-09-15 12:14:35 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-dad78da2d996eb9b2e00 received 5391871 . . . (first worker received the task and start working on it) . . 2022-09-15 12:20:28 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-c0e6a4e6e9d1d9d05000 received 5391871 (second worker received the same task and start working on it. And finished right away and ack the message) . . 2022-09-15 12:22:15 ecs-autoscale-celery-30-autoscale-celery-dad78da2d996eb9b2e00 succeeded (first worker finally finished and tries to ack on the message) Getting the following exception message: Message Couldn't ack 206, reason:"BrokenPipeError(32, 'Broken pipe')" Any idea on how I should avoid this problem?

issue.title: Support task pool shutdowns on idle
issue.body:
<!--
Please fill this template entirely and do not erase parts of it.
We reserve the right to close without a response
feature requests which are incomplete.
-->
# Checklist
<!--
To check an item on the list replace [ ] with [x].
-->

- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Feature+Request%22+)
  for similar or identical feature requests.
- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Feature%22+)
  for existing proposed implementations of this feature.
- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master)
  to find out if the same feature was already implemented in the
  master branch.
- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues
  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).

## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates
<!--
Please make sure to search and mention any related issues
or possible duplicates to this issue as requested by the checklist above.

This may or may not include issues in other repositories that the Celery project
maintains or other repositories that are dependencies of Celery.

If you don't know how to mention issues, please refer to Github's documentation
on the subject: https://help.github.com/en/articles/autolinked-references-and-urls#issues-and-pull-requests
-->

#### Related Issues

- Could not find anything for the key terms I searched

#### Possible Duplicates

- This seems similar to where a celery worker could be "bursted" and shutdown once the queue is empty here #6687. Would be a similar feature

# Brief Summary
<!--
Please include a brief summary of what the feature does
and why it is needed.
-->

Add the ability to shutdown a worker/pool, not entirely knowledgeable of underlying processes, when a queue is empty. I currently have the issue with tensorflow not deallocating GPU and the only solution would be to use multiprocessing, which I presume celery uses under the hood for certain pools, and it seems janky to have a task start another process, which just complicates things. Thus a method of "restarting" the pool after no tasks have been submitted for X amount of time would be nice.

# Design

## Architectural Considerations
<!--
If more components other than Celery are involved,
describe them here and the effect it would have on Celery.
-->
None

## Proposed Behavior
<!--
Please describe in detail how this feature is going to behave.
Describe what happens in case of failures as well if applicable.
-->

It would be nice to start a celery worker have it process whatever is in the queue and once it's done close/restart the pool process so that any allocated memory would be cleared. This is sort of similar to max-tasks-per-child, but that I noticed only restarts when a NEW task is assigned not when it's idle.

Some logic that would make this work better is that the pool wouldn't restart unless if it has already processed some tasks. In my case the queue could be empty majority of the time, but I occasionally have some peak GPU load for site tensorflow stuff and would like the memory to be cleared once the queue sits empty for let's say 5 minutes. I've looked at tf issues and it seems like there really isn't any non-obscure way to clear the memory without ending the process/clearing cuda/resetting the device which is not what I want. 

## Proposed UI/UX
<!--
Please provide your ideas for the API, CLI options,
configuration key names etc. that will be introduced for this feature.
-->

Add a flag of the sort, possibly way better names, `--child-empty-timeout Xs` which would reset the worker after X seconds of idle AFTER processing something.

## Diagrams
<!--
Please include any diagrams that might be relevant
to the implementation of this feature such as:
* Class Diagrams
* Sequence Diagrams
* Activity Diagrams
You can drag and drop images into the text box to attach them to this issue.
-->
N/A

## Alternatives
<!--
If you have considered any alternative implementations
describe them in detail below.
-->

Simply have the `max-tasks-per-child` terminate and recreate the pool immediately after the N tasks is complete.

issue.title: SoftTimeLimitExceeded exception does not raise with embedded worker
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7871
Originally posted by **voqtuyen** November 2, 2022 I have a test case with the following files conftest.py ```python import pytest pytest_plugins = ("celery.contrib.pytest", ) @pytest.fixture(scope='session') def celery_config(): return { 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'rpc://' } ``` tasks.py ```python import time from celery import Celery from conftest import celery_config app = Celery() app.conf.update({ 'broker_url': 'memory://', 'result_backend': 'cache+memcached://memcached:11211', 'soft_time_limit': 1 }) @app.task(bind=True, max_retries=2, soft_time_limit=1) def my_task(self, x, y): time.sleep(5) return x + y ``` tests_all.py ```python import pytest from tasks import app, my_task from celery.contrib.testing.worker import start_worker def test_my_task(): with start_worker(app, perform_ping_check=False, loglevel="INFO"): result = my_task.apply([2, 3], throw=True) result.get() ``` However, when I run pytest test_all.py does not raise SoftTimeLimitExceeded exception? Is there any wrong or what is the correct way to unittest it!

issue.title: At Least One Feature Request or Bug Fix Per Month Plan
issue.body:
Hi, all paid users,

 Firstly, thanks for your support! That means a lot to me. And for those who contributed to this project before by OpenCollective or code or other ways, please contact me and I will give you a free license.

This project is **five years old**, and I have maintained this project for five years. Over the past year, I didn't spend lots of time on this project because I've been busy with work, and there have been fewer updates. But I still keep doing bug fixes and small feature requests.  

Please believe that I have put unparalleled energy into this project. Feature requests and bug fixes are not done without any effort. For the sustainable development of this project, I will make some parts of this project (the C# part is completely rewritten) and the new ones added in the future as paid features.

**And, the open-source part of this project will still stay free, and free for always.**

Now I'm trying to start an "At Least One Feature Request or Bug Fix Per Month Plan", which means that I will at least make one feature request or bug fix done every month for paid users, and this plugin will update monthly. This basically improves the value of this plugin for paid users and makes this plugin live longer and better.

Please just fire your feature request or bug report, and I will try to fix them. And don't forget to upload your screenshots of "Help -> Register or Manage Licenses". And if someone else already fired a feature request or bug report, please 👍 for that.

Happy coding~

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

Runs in azure, BE in App service, celery in container instance, Postresql and ServiceBus Start celery `celery multi start 3 -A proj -P gevent --loglevel=INFO -E --logfile=$logfile --pidfile=/var/pid/celery/%n.pid --statedb=/var/db/%n.state` ``` @shared_task def create_task(): result = True return result ```

# Expected Behavior Shouldnt disconnect or stop receiving messages. It should show an error message. # Actual Behavior celery in some time stops receiving messages from broker or wont receiving messages from broker. Our healthcheck send every 10s task to celery and check response if pending status is longer then 3-5m, calls `celery multi restart -A proj -P gevent --loglevel=INFO -E --logfile=$logfile --pidfile=/var/pid/celery/%n.pid --statedb=/var/db/%n.state` and then it again doing his job When we turn off healthcheck same result. We can see the messages in service bus but celery doesnt pickup them. We already talked to azure support about infrastructure problem, everything works fine on their side. # Logs ```` [2022-10-11 00:13:15,590: INFO/MainProcess] Task issue.title: Canvas starting with a group does not respect a countdown applied to whole canvas
issue.body:
# Checklist - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [ ] This has already been asked to the [discussions forum](https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions) first. - [x] I have read the relevant section in the [contribution guide](https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/master/contributing.html#other-bugs) on reporting bugs. - [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Bug+Report%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for similar or identical bug reports. (#4405 may be related, but I'm not sure) - [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Bugfix%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22) for existing proposed fixes. - [ ] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/master) to find out if the bug was already fixed in the master branch. - [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway). #4405 may be related, as mentioned above ## Mandatory Debugging Information - [x] I have included the output of ``celery -A proj report`` in the issue. (if you are not able to do this, then at least specify the Celery version affected). - [x] I have verified that the issue exists against the `master` branch of Celery. - [x] I have included the contents of ``pip freeze`` in the issue. - [ ] I have included all the versions of all the external dependencies required to reproduce this bug. ## Optional Debugging Information - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one Python version and/or implementation. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one version of the message broker and/or result backend. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one operating system. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue on more than one workers pool. - [ ] I have tried reproducing the issue with autoscaling, retries, ETA/Countdown & rate limits disabled. - [x] I have tried reproducing the issue after downgrading and/or upgrading Celery and its dependencies. ## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates #### Related Issues - #4405 #### Possible Duplicates - None ## Environment & Settings **Celery version**: 5.3.0b1 (dawn-chorus)
celery report Output:

software -> celery:5.3.0b1 (dawn-chorus) kombu:5.3.0b2 py:3.8.12 billiard:4.0.2 redis:4.1.4 platform -> system:Linux arch:64bit, ELF kernel version:5.4.0-131-generic imp:CPython loader -> celery.loaders.app.AppLoader settings -> transport:redis results:redis:/// accept_content: ['json', 'pickle'] event_serializer: 'json' result_serializer: 'pickle' task_serializer: 'pickle' broker_url: 'redis://localhost:6379//' deprecated_settings: None result_backend: 'redis:///'

# Steps to Reproduce ## Required Dependencies * **Minimal Python Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Celery Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Kombu Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal OS and/or Kernel Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Broker Client Version**: N/A or Unknown * **Minimal Result Backend Client Version**: N/A or Unknown ### Python Packages
pip freeze Output:

adc-streaming==2.0.0 amqp==5.1.1 astroid==2.4.2 backports.entry-points-selectable==1.1.0 billiard==4.0.2 cachy==0.3.0 celery @ git+https://github.com/celery/celery.git@e0b0af6c7af9f7a127ae0321dc4e798433c89592 certifi==2021.10.8 cffi==1.15.1 charset-normalizer==2.1.1 click==8.1.3 click-didyoumean==0.3.0 click-plugins==1.1.1 click-repl==0.2.0 confluent-kafka==1.8.2 crashtest==0.3.1 cryptography==36.0.2 Deprecated==1.2.13 distlib==0.3.2 filelock==3.0.12 future==0.18.2 hop-client==0.5.0 idna==3.4 igwn-auth-utils==0.3.1 isort==5.6.3 kombu==5.3.0b2 lazy-object-proxy==1.4.3 ligo-gracedb==2.8.0 lockfile==0.12.2 mccabe==0.6.1 msgpack==1.0.2 packaging==21.3 pastel==0.2.1 pkginfo==1.7.1 platformdirs==2.3.0 pluggy==1.0.0 prompt-toolkit==3.0.28 pycparser==2.21 PyJWT==2.6.0 pylev==1.4.0 pylint==2.6.0 pyparsing==3.0.7 pytz==2021.3 redis==4.1.4 requests==2.28.1 safe-netrc==1.0.0 scitokens==1.7.2 shellingham==1.4.0 six==1.16.0 toml==0.10.2 tqdm==4.62.3 typing_extensions==4.4.0 urllib3==1.26.12 vine==5.0.0 virtualenv==20.7.2 wcwidth==0.2.5 wrapt==1.13.3 xmltodict==0.12.0

### Other Dependencies

N/A

## Minimally Reproducible Test Case

Project tree ```bash $ tree proj/ proj/ ├── __init__.py └── tasks.py ``` File contents ```bash $ cat proj/__init__.py from celery import Celery app = Celery('tasks', broker = 'redis://') app.conf['result_backend'] = app.conf.broker_url app.add_defaults( dict( accept_content = ['json', 'pickle'], event_serializer = 'json', result_serializer = 'pickle', task_serializer = 'pickle' ) ) app.autodiscover_tasks([__name__]) $ cat proj/tasks.py from . import app @app.task def add(x, y): return x + y @app.task def prod(x, y): return x * y ``` Start worker with ```bash $ celery -A proj worker -l info -c 2 ``` Then run following script ```python from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ```

# Expected Behavior Since a countdown has been placed, no task should execute until the countdown has expired. # Actual Behavior If a canvas starts with a `group`, and has chained tasks, the group is executed right away. For example in my minimal script above, there is the following canvas ``` canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ) canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async(countdown=10) ``` The `group` containing the two `add` tasks are evaluated rightaway in the queue. The timeout kicks in only after this. This is seen in the log of the worker (see timestamp of result 3, 7 vs. 11, 15, 19): ``` [2022-10-24 23:10:04,176: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: searching for neighbors [2022-10-24 23:10:04,177: WARNING/MainProcess] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:10:05,183: INFO/MainProcess] mingle: all alone [2022-10-24 23:10:05,201: INFO/MainProcess] celery@deep-ThinkPad-P53 ready. [2022-10-24 23:13:33,585: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,586: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] received [2022-10-24 23:13:33,589: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ce4dfe2e-6188-4762-ae17-8bcda6c6124a] succeeded in 0.002615050001622876s: 3 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,591: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-2] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-2] Task proj.tasks.add[e89c93a0-ae5f-482e-a5a2-6afb4e8168d3] succeeded in 0.00721587799853296s: 7 [2022-10-24 23:13:33,594: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,597: WARNING/ForkPoolWorker-1] No hostname was supplied. Reverting to default 'localhost' [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[864c3c54-5569-4a82-98d7-7aceaf9f4eee] succeeded in 0.008149747001880314s: 11 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,601: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,602: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[a6d1d655-5cae-4248-bdeb-5844e8c3efce] succeeded in 0.0008764769991103094s: 15 [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/MainProcess] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] received [2022-10-24 23:13:43,603: INFO/ForkPoolWorker-1] Task proj.tasks.add[ff2fa778-d6ef-4976-ac21-f46ebd9dd88d] succeeded in 0.00035578700044425204s: 19 ``` The tasks starting `ce4dfe2e` and `e89c93a0` are received and are evaluated immediately giving results 3 and 7. The tasks that are chained to the group evaluate after the timeout is expired (note the timing for the task starting `864c3c54`). ### A few other observations - If there are chained tasks after the group, then setting `countdown` to the group directly is not respected. For example, changing minimal example to ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) # set countdown here canvas |= tasks.add.si(5, 6) canvas |= tasks.add.si(7, 8) canvas |= tasks.add.si(9, 10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` Gives all results rightaway: ``` Result = 19 Time elapsed(s) 0.03932476043701172 ``` However, if there are no chained tasks i.e., just the `group`, then the behavior is as expect. For example, ``` from time import time from celery import group from proj import tasks canvas = group( tasks.add.si(1, 2), tasks.add.si(3, 4) ).set(countdown=10) t = time() r = canvas.apply_async() print("Result = ", r.get()) print("Time elapsed(s)", time() -t) ``` will print ``` Result = [3, 7] Time elapsed(s) 10.034985542297363 ```

issue.title: Timers registered in worker start are getting cancelled on consumer close
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7843
Originally posted by **meensu23** October 21, 2022 I register some tasks during worker start ``` class WorkerBoot(bootsteps.StartStopStep): requires = {"celery.worker.components:Pool", "celery.worker.components:Timer"} ... def __init__(self, worker, **kwargs) -> None: def start(self, worker): ... worker.timer.call_repeatedly( self.state_refresh_interval, self.some_function, (worker,), priority=10, ) ... ``` What I observe is after a connection loss (with amq) and restart the above timer does not fire. I printed the timer ref above and I see the same timer ref being used in worker and consumer. And as per https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/34533ab44d2a6492004bc3df44dc04ad5c6611e7/celery/worker/consumer/consumer.py#L443 I see the timer is being cleared. ``` consumerboot consumer.timer= workerboot worker.timer= ``` Does worker and consumer use the same timer - documentation seem to suggest they use different (https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/extending.html?highlight=consumer%20boot#id8). What timer should I be using in the worker?

issue.title: Celery fills Redis Broker with results without setting TTL - resulting in OOM of Redis
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/celery/celery/discussions/7776
Originally posted by **Flauschbaellchen** September 27, 2022 I have an issue in our application: When running Celery tasks, Celery keeps track of the tasks saving metadata (and the task's result) into the Broker's database. This data is however never deleted, which results in OOM of Redis eventually. ### Details I'm using the Redis backend. After running 1-3 tasks, the Redis database consists of the following entries: ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> keys * 1) "_kombu.binding.w3syse.queues.default" 2) "_kombu.binding.celery.pidbox" 3) "7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786" 4) "_kombu.binding.celeryev" ``` (I've set `task_default_queue = "w3syse.queues.default"`) Celery created the additional key `7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786` which tracks a task. The content is like the following: ``` {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "SUCCESS", "result": null, "traceback": null, "children": []} {"task_id": "9130013f-cabe-4ae2-9c44-8dc78272526b", "status": "STARTED", "result": {"pid": 1, "hostname": "celery@worker-server-7889c959d7-5mcmp"}, "traceback": null, "children": []} ``` The issue is, that those keys are never deleted, spamming the whole Redis database to such an extend, that the size is greater than the RAM of the machine and Redis is not able to run anymore (64GB+). This happens regularly if running several hundreds of tasks per second. After some research, I've found that the RedisBackend should be responsible of deleting such keys automatically on its own: https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/4f54119b822374533934943fa41ba68011295489/celery/backends/redis.py#L203 The TTL is 1 day (default) and can be adjusted by setting `result_expires` (see: https://docs.celeryq.dev/en/stable/userguide/configuration.html#result-expires). I tried to set it to `5` (5 seconds), however, when checking the TTL of the key, Redis always returns `-1`, which means "No expire": ``` 127.0.0.1:6379> ttl 7a31e86c-24fe-3722-8f2f-997e0cbf9786 (integer) -1 ``` ### Environment Versions of packages: * celery[redis]==5.2.7 * django-celery-beat==2.3.0 * kombu==5.2.4 * redis==3.5.3 Redis server is 7.0.4. Other settings: ``` CELERY_RESULT_BACKEND = "rpc://" CELERY_ACCEPT_CONTENT = ["application/json"] CELERY_TASK_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_RESULT_SERIALIZER = "json" CELERY_TIMEZONE = TIME_ZONE CELERY_ENABLE_UTC = True CELERY_BEAT_SCHEDULER = "django_celery_beat.schedulers:DatabaseScheduler" CELERY_TASK_SEND_SENT_EVENT = True CELERY_WORKER_SEND_TASK_EVENTS = True CELERY_TASK_TRACK_STARTED = True ``` Can someone reproduce this issue/bug or can give me a hint if I need to adjust a setting? - Thanks a lot!

issue.title: ImportError: cannot import name 'XXX' from 'kombu'
issue.body:
Hi, I found some errors about import like this:

```
❯❯ pip install kombu
....
❯❯ python
Python 3.7.12 (default, Jan 26 2022, 16:07:16)
[Clang 13.0.0 (clang-1300.0.29.3)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> from kombu import Exchange
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 1, in <module>
ImportError: cannot import name 'Exchange' from 'kombu' (***/.pyenv/versions/temp/lib/python3.7/site-packages/kombu/__init__.py)
```

All packages:

```
❯❯ pip list
Package            Version
------------------ -------
amqp               5.1.1
cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 5.0.0
kombu              5.2.4
pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0
typing_extensions  4.4.0
vine               5.0.0
zipp               3.9.0
```

The possible reason may be the `importlib-metadata`:

```
❯❯ pip install importlib-metadata==4.13.0
....
Successfully installed importlib-metadata-4.13.0
❯❯ python
Python 3.7.12 (default, Jan 26 2022, 16:07:16)
[Clang 13.0.0 (clang-1300.0.29.3)] on darwin
Type "help", "copyright", "credits" or "license" for more information.
>>> from kombu import Exchange
>>> 
```

Everything all right and now the packages are:

```
❯❯ pip list
Package            Version
------------------ -------
amqp               5.1.1
cached-property    1.5.2
importlib-metadata 4.13.0
kombu              5.2.4
pip                22.2.2
setuptools         47.1.0
typing_extensions  4.4.0
vine               5.0.0
zipp               3.9.0
```

The only difference is the version of `importlib-metadata`.

issue.title: SQS Batch SendMessage
issue.body:
Hi all,

We're recently transitioned from using SQS natively to using Celery. We have some use cases where we send a bunch of tasks - for example, canceling every payment belonging to an entity. When we started using celery we noticed that each message is enqueued individually, and there's nothing in the documentation that I could find. Searching through Kombu, I see that batch get is supported, but batch put does not seem to be supported. In my ideal world, we can support batch messaging in Celery to improve our app's throughput. Let me know if that makes sense!

Docs: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/APIReference/API_SendMessageBatch.html
